metadata.description: Mantle & Repeater walk into a bar at Christmas... Happy holidays!

metadata.name: Focused MINd #48
metadata.description:
Although it looks like this piece is a metaphor for a focused mind, actually the title was chosen after the piece was finished :-) .

Basically a focused mind have a more or less clear direction but, no matter how deep in the flow one is, there are occasional thought that stray away and choose their own path.


The piece is built entirely on thi.ng/umbrella libraries and template:

https://github.com/thi-ng/fxhash-tpl

Initial resolution: 1280 x 720

Keyboard shortcuts

- 2 : download png @ 2 x resolution
- 4 : download png @ 4 x resolution
- x : download canvas as PNG @ current resolution
- s : download SVG version @ current resolution

metadata.name: Dance of lines and shapes #31
metadata.description:
This collection is a combination of different lines and shapes.
It contains 10 different layers, the first layer contains backgrounds.
The second, fourth, sixth and seventh layers contain shapes made with lines.
The third and eighth layers contain different shapes.
The fifth layer of shapes is fixed with dots.
The ninth layer is noises and the last layer is frame.

i hope you like my new collection.

metadata.name: Unfamiliar Directions #321
metadata.description:
"Unfamiliar Directions" is my submission for #fxhashturnsone. This project is a study of grid walking and avoidance. While working on this p5.js sketch, the renders looked like a combination of circuits and chips on an electronic board (two of the main functions being 'circuit' and 'chip.'). The more I played with it in fx(stdio), the more it started to resemble maps and directions given by a mapping app on my phone. Some paths seem straightforward, from point A to point B. Other times, the directions weave right through buildings and seem to end at about the same place as the start. 

I hope you enjoy this project, and happy #fxhashturnsone!

Primary Splits:
50% Donation to the Processing Foundation

Royalties Splits:
50% Donation to minter

Dependencies:
processing/p5.js
lodash/lodash
Jam3/nice-color-palettes
@liamegan1/fxhash-helpers
@altesc/stdio

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: full print size (see features for dimensions)

License: CC-BY

Please find me on Twitter and Instagram at @natenolting.

metadata.name: The Beaten Path #70
metadata.description:
There's always an internal struggle between walking on the beaten path or off of it. And that comes from the illusion that the choice is really a thing. Although we are slaves of our internal processes, we shall never be the slaves of others. 

Keyboard shortcuts

- 1 : render @ original resolution
- 2 : render @ 2 x resolution
- 4 : render @ 4 x resolution
- x : download canvas as PNG @ current resolution

The project uses thi.ng/umbrella and fast-simplex-noise packages.

metadata.name: Richter #220
metadata.description:
Richter is the second collaboration of Richard Nadler and Leander Herzog, following their first project called Gerhard. A generative animation based on multiple layers of color and data, mixed, moved and painted over in realtime. Some fragments stick to the canvas while others get discarded to leave the existing layers visible, allowing a complex surface to emerge and build up over time.
 
Richter works with data from 4 of 24 highres images, 30mb in total. This is the maximum size fxhash allows for a project and three times more than Gerhard. Richard Nadler created stunning new textures, enabling more variation in composition and detail to emerge at much higher resolution. Leander Herzog created the code for the interplay between the layers, motion and interactions. Richter elevates the approach from Gerhard with new methods for the realtime rendering process and new features like offline-first caching. Both artists use different tools and are not aware of the details of each others process, meeting through the interface of pixels as data.
 
Richter is featured in the exhibition "Generative Abstraction" at Expanded.art in Berlin.
 
- Click to start a new layer of motion and color.
- Doubleclick to enter fullscreen.
- Press s to save the canvas.
- Append ?dpr=4 to the url to increase the resolution.

leanderherzog.ch/2023/richter/
leanderherzog.ch/2022/gerhard/
fxhash.xyz/generative/17030/
